	timestamp = {Sat, 15 Nov 2025 13:45:36 +0100},
	biburl = {https://dblp.org/rec/conf/esorics/AustaMD25.bib},
	bibsource = {dblp computer science bibliography, https://dblp.org},
	abstract = {While interest in the open RISC-V instruction set architecture is growing, tools to assess\xa0the security of concrete processor implementations are lacking. There\xa0are dedicated tools and benchmarks for common microarchitectural side-channel vulnerabilities for popular processor families such as Intel x86-64 or ARM, but not for RISC-V. In this paper we describe our efforts in porting\xa0an Intel x86-64 benchmark suite for cache-based timing vulnerabilities to RISC-V. We then use this benchmark to evaluate the security of three commercially available RISC-V processors, the T-Head C910 and the SiFive U54 and\xa0U74 cores. We observe that the C910 processor exhibits more distinct timing types than the other processors, leading to the assumption that\xa0code running on the C910 would be exposed to more microarchitectural vulnerability sources. In addition, our evaluation reveals that \\(37.5\\%\\) of the vulnerabilities covered by the benchmark exist in all processors, while only \\(6.8\\%\\)\xa0are absent from all cores. Our work, in particular the ported benchmark,\xa0aims to support RISC-V processor designers to identify leakage sources early\xa0in their designs and to support the development of countermeasures.}
}


